## Task 2: Student Digital Portfolio
**Platforms Chosen:** GitHub, LinkedIn, and Kaggle.  
**Platform Utility:**
1. **GitHub:** Used for version control and showcasing my technical projects and coding progress.
2. **LinkedIn:** My professional "living resume" used for networking with alumni and tracking industry trends.
3. **Kaggle:** A platform for data science competitions and learning from shared datasets.

**Four-Year Plan:**
Over the next four years, I plan to use these platforms as a chronological record of my growth. I will update GitHub weekly with lab work and personal projects. On LinkedIn, I intend to connect with at least two industry professionals per month and share certifications I earn. Kaggle will be my primary resource for extracurricular learning in data analysis, helping me build a portfolio that is ready for internship applications by my third year.

---

## Task 3: Coding & Collaboration Platforms
**Platforms Used:** HackerRank and Google Workspace.  
**Building & Practice:**
I completed the "Python: If-Else" challenge on HackerRank to refresh my logic-building skills. Additionally, I built a "Digital Literacy Awareness Quiz" using Google Forms. The quiz includes multiple-choice questions on password security and a short-answer section for students to define "Phishing." I linked this to a Google Sheet to automatically track responses and analyze the average digital literacy score of my peers.

**Academic Benefits:**
These tools are vital for my academic journey. HackerRank prepares me for technical interview environments, while Google Workspace streamlines group projects. Knowing how to create forms and analyze data in sheets allows me to conduct research and gather peer feedback efficiently, which is a core requirement for engineering and management modules.

---

## Task 4: Professional Email & Etiquette
**Digital Communication Reflection:**
I once read about a candidate who lost a high-paying job offer because they replied to a recruiter's email with "K thx" and no signature. This lack of professionalism signaled to the company that the candidate might be careless in client communications. If the student had simply followed basic etiquette—using a formal salutation, a full sentence of gratitude, and a professional sign-off—the outcome would have been entirely different. It taught me that in the digital world, your text is your first impression; if it’s sloppy, people assume your work is sloppy too.

---

## Task 5: Cybercrime Awareness & Prevention
**Cybercrime Reflection:**
While researching UPI/Online Payment Fraud, I was surprised by the psychological tactics used in "collect-request" scams. Fraudsters don't just use technical hacks; they use "urgency" and "fear" to trick users into entering their PIN to *receive* money, which is logically impossible. 

**Personal Habit Change:**
As a result of this research, I have committed to never clicking on "promotional" links sent via SMS, even if they look like they are from my bank. I have also enabled SIM-card locking and biometric authentication for all my financial apps to add an extra layer of security beyond just a 4-digit PIN.
